#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:24
msgid "Environnement variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:26
msgid ""
"Environmental variables `have been around since DOS "
"<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Environment_variable#DOS>`_. They can make"
" your (and my) life easier."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:31
msgid "Program directories"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:33
msgid ""
"Not every system uses ``C:\\`` as the main drive. Some enterprises use "
"folder redirection, and relocate the Documents folder. Some places in the"
" world don't speak English and their directories reflect that. **Use "
"those environmental variables to make your programs \"just work\"**:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:39
msgid ""
"``%SystemDrive%`` is the drive where ``%SystemRoot%`` is located. You "
"most likely don't need to actually know this;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:42
msgid ""
"``%SystemRoot%`` is where the Windows directory is located. You hopefully"
" don't care about this. Leave the Windows directory alone;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:45
msgid ""
"``%ProgramFiles%`` is where you should place your program files, "
"preferable in a ``Company\\Program`` structure;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:48
msgid ""
"``%ProgramFiles(x86)%`` is where you should place your 32-bit program "
"files. Please update them for 64-bit. 32-bit will eventually be "
"unsupported, and business will be waiting for you to get your shit "
"together for far longer than necessary;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:53
msgid ""
"``%ProgramData%`` is where you should store data that isn't user "
"specific, but still needs to be written to by users (Users don't have "
"write access to this folder either)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:57
msgid ""
"Your program shouldn't require administrator rights to run as you "
"shouldn't have us writing to the ``%ProgramFiles%`` directory. Also, "
"don't throw executables in here."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:61
msgid ""
"``%Temp%`` is where you can process temporary data. Place that data "
"within a unique folder name (maybe a generated GUID perhaps) so you don't"
" cause an incompatibility with another program. Windows will even do the "
"cleanup for you. Don't put temporary data in in ``%ProgramData%`` or "
"``%ProgramFiles%``;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:67
msgid ""
"``%AppData%`` is where you can save the user running your program "
"settings. This is a fantastic location that can by synced with a server "
"and used to quickly and easily migrate a user to a new machine and keep "
"all of their program settings. Don't put giant or ephemeral files here."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:72
msgid ""
"You could be the cause of a very slow login if you put the wrong stuff "
"here and a machine needs to sync it up. **DON'T PUT YOUR PROGRAM FILES "
"HERE**. The business decides what software is allowed to run, not you and"
" a bunch of users who may not know how their company's environment is set"
" up;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:77
#, python-format
msgid ""
"``%LocalAppData%`` is where you can put bigger files that are specific to"
" a user and computer. You don't need to sync up a thumbnail cache. They "
"won't be transferred when a user migrates to a new machine, or logs into "
"a new VDI station, or terminal server. **DON'T PUT YOUR PROGRAM FILES "
"HERE EITHER**;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:85
msgid ""
"You can get these directory paths through `API calls "
"<https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/shell/known-folders>`_ as"
" well if you don't/can't use environmental variables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:90
msgid "Logs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:92
msgid ""
"Use the `Windows Event Log <https://docs.microsoft.com/en-"
"us/windows/win32/eventlog/event-logging>`_ for logging. It'll handle the "
"rotation for you and a sysadmin can forward those logs or do whatever "
"they need to. You can even make your own little area just for your "
"program."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:99
msgid "Error codes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:101
msgid ""
"Use `documented Error Codes <https://docs.microsoft.com/en-"
"us/windows/win32/debug/system-error-codes>`_ when exiting your program."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:106
msgid "Printing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:108
msgid ""
"Use the `Windows printing API <https://docs.microsoft.com/en-"
"us/windows/win32/printdocs/printdocs-printing>`_ and do not use direct "
"printing in your program."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:113
msgid "Distribution"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:115
msgid ""
"Distribute your program in `MSI <https://docs.microsoft.com/en-"
"us/windows/win32/msi/installer-function-reference>`_ (or now probably "
"`MSIX <https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/msix/overview>`_). It is "
"the standard for Windows installation files (even though Microsoft "
"sometimes doesn't use it themselves)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:120
msgid ""
"`Sign your installation file and executables <https://docs.microsoft.com"
"/en-us/windows/win32/appxpkg/how-to-sign-a-package-using-signtool>`_. "
"It's how we know it's valid and can whitelist in `AppLocker "
"<https://docs.microsoft.com/en-"
"us/powershell/module/applocker/?view=win10-ps>`_ or other policies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:126
msgid ""
"Applocker and `Software Restriction Policies "
"<https://dev.tranquil.it/samba/en/samba_config_client/client_SRP.html>`_ "
"can be very effective and the management of these policies can be made "
"simpler with WAPT."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:133
msgid "Update"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:135
msgid ""
"Want to have your application update for you? That can be fine if the "
"business is okay with it. You can create a scheduled task or service that"
" runs elevated to allow for this without granting the user admin rights. "
"I like the way Chrome Enterprise does it: gives a GPO to set update "
"settings, the max version it will update to (say 81.* to allow all minor "
"updates automatically and major versions are manual), and a service. They"
" also have a GPO to prevent user-based installs;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:145
msgid ""
"WAPT is designed for businesses that don't allow users to run software "
"updates, which is the policy often chosen in large security conscious "
"enterprises."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:149
msgid "Version numbers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:151
msgid ""
"Use `semantic versioning <https://semver.org/>`_ (should go in the "
"version property in the installer file and in the Add/Remove Programs "
"list, not in the application title) and have a `changelog "
"<https://keepachangelog.com/>`_. You can also have your installer "
"download at a predictable location to allow for automation. A published "
"update path is nice too;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:159
msgid ""
"If you apply this practice, then you will make system administrators who "
"deploy your software updates using the :ref:`WAPT function def_update() "
"<envdev_setup>` **very happy**!!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:165
msgid "GPO"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:167
msgid "ADMX templates are dope;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:171
msgid ""
"We completely agree with you _benwa on this at Tranquil IT. If developers"
" advise their customers to use GPOs to deploy their software or system or"
" users settings, then, **they must know that GPOs are not fully "
"reliable**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:175
msgid ""
"Instead, package your software, your system and user configurations using"
" WAPT. A :file:`setup.py` is so much easier than an :mimetype:`xml` file "
"for system admins to audit before deploying."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:179
msgid ""
"WAPT packages can be applied recursively to trees of Organisational "
"Units, so your WAPT package will behave in production exactly as a GPO "
"would, **just much easier**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:185
msgid "License dongles"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:187
msgid ""
"USB license dongles are a sin. Use a regular software or network license."
" I'm sure there are off the shelf ones so you don't have to reinvent the "
"wheel;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:192
msgid ""
"You can make your software accept a licence key as a parameter in your "
":mimetype:`msi` executable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:195
msgid ""
"WAPT can be used to assign licence keys to individual workstations at "
"install using a :ref:`method that ensures that the licence key can not be"
" read during transport <encryting_sensitive_data_in_package>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:199
msgid ""
"Then, if you want your software to call home to check on the validity of "
"the licence, make the routine work with :ref:`proxies "
"<proper_use_of_proxy_in_software>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:205
msgid "Networking"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:207
msgid ""
"Don't use that damn custom IPv4 input field. Use FDQNs. IPv6 had been "
"around since 1998 and will work with your software if you just give it a "
"chance;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:211
msgid ""
"The Windows Firewall (can't really say much about third party ones) is "
"going to stay on. Know the difference between an incoming and outgoing "
"rule. Most likely, your server will need incoming. Most likely, you "
"clients won't even need an outgoing. Set those up at install time, not "
"launch time. Use Firewall Groups so it's easy to filter. Don't use Any "
"rules if you can help it. The goal isn't to make it work, it's to make it"
" work securely. If you don't use version numbers in your install path, "
"you might not even have to remake those rules after every upgrade;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:222
msgid ""
"Proxies are good for hygiene and proxies are now a default security "
"feature not just in corporate IT environments, but even on small "
"networks. Making your software not compatible with proxies will require "
"the network administrators of your customer to make and maintain special "
"rules in their firewall, just for you. It is easy to code your software "
"to work with proxies, so please do!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:231
msgid "PDFs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:233
msgid ""
"Don't ship a software that requires allowing javascript to run in PDF "
"readers. Business logic should be run before outputting to a PDF, not "
"after."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/wapt-software-best-practices.rst:238
msgid ""
":mimetype:`PDF` files is the file format people use by default to "
"exchange documents. PDF readers are meant to display documents, not "
"execute unsigned programs."
msgstr ""
